# ⚙️ EFK Setup Using Helm

The EFK stack can be deployed easily using **Helm charts**.

We will install:

1. Elasticsearch
2. Fluent Bit
3. Kibana

---

# 🗄 Step 1 — Create Storage Class

Elasticsearch requires persistent storage.

Create `storage-class.yml`

```yaml
apiVersion: storage.k8s.io/v1
kind: StorageClass
metadata:
  name: dev-storage-class
provisioner: kubernetes.io/hostpath
```

Apply the configuration:

```bash
kubectl apply -f storage-class.yml
```

Verify storage class:

```bash
kubectl get sc
```

---

# 📂 Step 2 — Create Namespace

Create a dedicated namespace for logging components.

```bash
kubectl create namespace logging
```

Verify namespace:

```bash
kubectl get ns
```

---

# 💾 Step 3 — Create Persistent Volume

Create `pv.yml`

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolume
metadata:
  name: elasticsearch-master
  namespace: logging
spec:
  capacity:
    storage: 20Gi
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  storageClassName: dev-storage-class
  persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Retain
  hostPath:
    path: /tmp
```

Apply PV:

```bash
kubectl apply -f pv.yml
```

Verify:

```bash
kubectl get pv -n logging
```

---

# 🔎 Step 4 — Install Elasticsearch

Download Elasticsearch Helm chart:

```bash
wget https://helm.elastic.co/helm/elasticsearch/elasticsearch-7.17.1.tgz
```

Extract the chart:

```bash
tar -xvf elasticsearch-7.17.1.tgz
```

Go inside directory:

```bash
cd elasticsearch
```

Edit `values.yaml` to include storage class:

```yaml
volumeClaimTemplate:
  accessModes: ["ReadWriteOnce"]
  storageClassName: dev-storage-class
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 5Gi
```

Install Elasticsearch:

```bash
helm install elasticsearch-repo . -f values.yaml -n logging
```

Verify:

```bash
kubectl get pods -n logging
```

---

# 📡 Step 5 — Install Fluent Bit

Download Fluent Bit Helm chart:

```bash
wget https://github.com/fluent/helm-charts/releases/download/fluent-bit-0.21.0/fluent-bit-0.21.0.tgz
```

Extract it:

```bash
tar -xvf fluent-bit-0.21.0.tgz
```

Go inside directory:

```bash
cd fluent-bit
```

Install Fluent Bit:

```bash
helm install fluent-bit . -f values.yaml -n logging
```

Fluent Bit will start collecting logs from Kubernetes nodes and forwarding them to Elasticsearch.

---

# 📊 Step 6 — Install Kibana

Download Kibana Helm chart:

```bash
wget https://helm.elastic.co/helm/kibana/kibana-7.17.3.tgz
```

Extract it:

```bash
tar -xvf kibana-7.17.3.tgz
```

Go inside directory:

```bash
cd kibana
```

Edit `values.yaml`:

Change service type from:

```
ClusterIP
```

to

```
NodePort
```

Example configuration:

```yaml
service:
  type: NodePort
  port: 5601
  nodePort: 30002
```

Install Kibana:

```bash
helm install kibana . -f values.yaml -n logging
```

---

# 🔍 Step 7 — Verify Deployment

Check pods:

```bash
kubectl get pods -n logging
```

Check services:

```bash
kubectl get svc -n logging
```

---

# 🌐 Step 8 — Access Kibana Dashboard

Access Kibana using:

```
http://Node-Public-IP:30002
```

Kibana dashboard allows you to:

* Search logs
* Analyze logs
* Monitor application activity
* Create visualization dashboards

